{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f78b5700-74c1-440e-b354-618f347938d9","content":"In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events API** in your `MauiProgram.cs` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android stop */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separated.\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.\n- Android exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, etc.\n- iOS exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.\n- Each handler receives the platform-native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f4adcc5a-949b-4cf9-b74d-a94e9d49293d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development, not a codebase-specific task.","outputTokens":374,"requestId":"77EC:32055B:7E78418:8CA88B4:69EABE39"},"id":"ab43b84a-fb83-4e57-b9b1-dc21b3bba914","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:50:09.487Z","parentId":"1726c55b-7c3c-4eb8-9517-344526569bf2"}
